  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Bamboo Conduit
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I split bamboo to guide the cold spring waters,
    And through the night they sing their gentle song—
    Trillings that never cease, a liquid murmur.

    When they flow here, even the deep ravine runs dry,
    Yet from their course a small basin brims and glistens.
    Their delicate voice trembles like a dream's soft sobbing,
    Their crystalline tone steeps the tea with subtle grace.

    Why lower the long rope of the frozen well?
    Why sit upon the silver bed and haul a hundred feet?
    No labor in this art—the bamboo brings what I desire.
  footnotes:
    - The 'silver bed' (銀床) likely refers to an elevated pavilion or platform, emphasizing the speaker's leisure and the effortless nature of obtaining water through the bamboo conduit.
    - The image of the 'frozen well rope' (寒綆) contrasts the traditional, laborious method of drawing water with the passive, natural flow achieved through the bamboo system.
